@Node INTR "Introduction to this PowerDOOR"

  -=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-
                        Introduction - What is it?
  -=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-

   This Door is basically a SysOp Paging System which allows users to
   attract the attention of a Bulletin Boards System Operator by
   running this Door. The Door will ask the User for a Reason to Page.
   When ran, The Door will perform an Alert on the SysOp's side. This
   can be specified in the Configuration file.

   The SysOp can simply answer the page using one of three available
   Gadgets. These gadgets are `Answer', `Busy' and `Cancel'...

  -=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-
                        What does this Door offer?
  -=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-
  
   This Door offers Five different Paging Systems which can be selected
   at Random by the Door itself or you can specify which of the Five
   you want to use by specifying in the Configuration File.

   @{" [0] " Link MAIN} Return to the Main Menu

@EndNode INTR

@Node INST "Installing PowerDOORS"

  -=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-
                     Installation of this PowerDOOR...
  -=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-

   All PowerDOORS are installed in the same way. Simply, make sure that
   there is a directory in your Doors directory or assignment called
   `POWER'. This is where all PowerDOORS are stored. If you do not have
   your DOORS directory assigned, then you should add an Assign to your
   Startup-Sequence or User-Startup File.

        C:Assign >NIL: DOORS: BBS:Doors/
                              ^^^^^^^^^^
                              Change this to your Doors directory path

   Now, Create a directory inside the `DOORS:Power/' Directory with
   the name of the Door. This is the word to the right of the `Power'
   in the Archive filename. So, For example, if the PowerDOOR was called
   PowerPAGE, then you would create a directory in the `DOORS:Power/'
   directory called `PAGE'.

   Now, Locate the Archive you downloaded or received. It will probably
   be in the `LhA' or `LZX' form. Simply use a version of `LhA' or `LZX'
   to Extract the files into the desired path.

    C:LhA x PowerPAGE_??.LHA DOORS:Power/RawUL/  \  Where `????' is the
                                                  } Name of the PowerDOOR
    C:LZX x PowerPAGE_??.LZX DOORS:Power/RawUL/  /  For example, `SEND'

   Now, all the files including some File Descriptions `File_ID.DIZ' and
   some Configuration files `Page.CFG'. Other files will also be
   included which are not Doors such as those that have the File
   Extension of `.Text'. These files are ANSIs. If you find a file with
   an extension of `DAT', then do not try and edit these.

   Now, In your MAXsBBS Menu Editor, Locate where you want to add this
   Paging Door and enter the following information in the Fields
   contained in the Menu Editor...

   Key   Function   Extra   Lo Acc   Hi Acc   Path/Filename
   ~~~   ~~~~~~~~   ~~~~~   ~~~~~~   ~~~~~~   ~~~~~~~~~~~~~
     ?         34       0        ?        ?   POWER:Page/Page <PAGER>

   Where <PAGER> is the Number of the Pager you would like to use.
   If no number is given, then the Door will use the setup specified
   in the Configuration File.

   @{" [0] " Link MAIN} Return to the Main Menu

@EndNode INST

@Node CONF "Configuring PowerDOORS"

  -=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-
                       Configuration of PowerDOORS
  -=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-

   All PowerDOORS are configured in the same way. In the PowerDOOR
   archive (or Directory if extracted), You will find file(s) with an
   extension of `.CFG', These are @{b}C@{ub}on@{b}F@{ub}i@{b}G@{ub}uration files.

   Simply load these Configuration (CFG) Files into a Text Editor and
   either follow the simple guide located at the end of the Configuration
   files or use the more complex guide which is located in the Door Guide.

  -=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-
    Layout for the Configuration                               PowerPAGE
  -=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-

  << @{b}Line 01@{ub} >> - @{i} User Name @{ui}
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~
   This line should contain the Name of the BBS SysOp or the Name of
   the User who will receive the Mail that people send when replying
   `Yes' to PowerPAGE when it asks the users if they would like to
   leave a message...

   ie. Techn!x

  << @{b}Line 02@{ub} >> - @{i} Boolean Option (Y or N) @{ui}
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~
   This line should contain either a `Y' or a `N' to represent
   whether or not, you would like to give the choice to your users
   of letting them send a Message to the SysOp if the SysOp is
   unavailable to Answer the Page...

   `Y' - The Users can Send Messages to the SysOp.
   `N' - The Users cannot Send Messages to the SysOp.

  << @{b}Line 03@{ub} >> - @{i} Number of Pagers Available @{ui}
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~
   This line should contain the Number of Pagers included in the
   current version of PowerPAGE. In this version (v2.0), There
   are FIVE different Pagers to choose from, meaning that this
   number should be between 1 and 5 but No Higher Than FIVE!

  << @{b}Line 04@{ub} >> - @{i} Pager to Use @{ui}
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~
   This Line should contain the Number of the Pager you would like
   to use. There are a choice of FIVE in this Version (v2.0), Meaning
   that you can put any number from `1' to `5', or you can put `0'
   which means the Door will select a Pager at Random on every use.

  << @{b}Line 05@{ub} >> - @{i} DOS Command (with Path) @{ui}
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~
   This Line should contain the Path and Filename of a DOS Command
   that will be ran during Paging. This should be something that will
   attract your attention such as a Sound Sample player or a Module
   Player. Included in the Archive is a Sample. Simply use any Sample
   player to play it...

  << @{b}Line 06@{ub} >> - @{i} End of Configuration @{ui}
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~
   As with all PowerDOORS, The Hash (#) at the end of the Configuration
   signifies its end. Any text after this Hash (either to the right or
   below it) will be ignored by the Door making it useful to add comments
   about the configuration below.
   
  -=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-

   Now, Save the Configuration File as a Plain ASCII File and not a
   Wordworth or other WP Document. Make sure that the File is saved in
   Plain ASCII otherwise it will not work.

   @{" [0] " Link MAIN} Return to the Main Menu

@EndNode CONF

@Node USIN "Using the PowerDOOR"

  -=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-
                           Using the PowerDOOR...
  -=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-

   When the Door is loaded, The User will be asked to enter a Reason
   why he or she wants to the Page the SysOp of the BBS.

   After the User has entered a Reason and pressed [RETURN], The
   Door will do three things...

     i)  It will open the PowerPAGE Control Window on the SysOps Side;
    ii)  It will launch the Alert DOS Command specified in the
         Configuration file;
   iii)  and Finally, It will begin the Paging Routines.

   Now, Once the Paging Routines begin, You will be able to see the
   PowerPAGE Control Window. This window will either be located on
   your MAXsBBS Screen or on the Workbench or any other Public Screen
   you may have open.

   Now, To answer the Page, Simply click on `Answer Page' and the Door
   will exit back to the BBS allowing you to select or load a Chat
   Door or whatever...

   To Cancel the Page, Simply click on the `Cancel' Gadget and the Door
   will act as if the SysOp wasn't in and the Pager had timed out. It
   will show the Resulting ANSI File and then Exit.

   To Busy the Page, Simply click on the `Busy' Gadget. The Door will
   now show the Busy ANSI file and exit.

   During Exit, The User will be asked if he or she wants to leave a
   message to the SysOp. If the User presses `Y' then a Message will
   be sent to the Person specified in the Configuration File.
   If `N' is pressed, then the Door will exit back to the BBS.

   @{" [0] " Link MAIN} Return to the Main Menu

@EndNode USIN

